      },
      {
        "content": "Richard Lemarchand says his game story began in 1991 in the rural west of England, on the eve of a videogame revolution. He was 23 years old, had just graduated from Oxford with a Physics & Philosophy degree, and was struggling with an undiagnosed situational depression while also searching for meaning in art, including videogames.",
        "title": "Lemarchand's 1991 starting point",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:22.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand describes getting hired by the rapidly expanding American game publisher MicroProse, which had a small British studio. He calls the job a stroke of luck because he had little professional experience but managed to win a position as a junior game designer.",
        "title": "First junior design job at MicroProse",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:22.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He reflects that the creative tinkering he had done as a child and teenager, which he once thought of as play, turned out to matter a great deal in game development. Once inside the studio, he threw himself into learning from his brilliant colleagues and treated the job as a chance to grow creatively.",
        "title": "Childhood tinkering became design value",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:23.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article frames Lemarchand as a legendary game designer who is writing about the importance and joy of playful storytelling. The piece is titled 'My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling' and is published by The MIT Press Reader.",
        "title": "Article framing and theme",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:23.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article includes a screenshot caption describing an 'Uncharted 2' peaceful village sequence in which Nathan Drake strolls through a Himalayan village on a sunny morning. This visual example suggests the article may connect game design to mood, atmosphere, and narrative pacing rather than only mechanics.",
        "title": "Uncharted 2 village sequence example",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:23.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand is identified in the article as the author of 'A Playful Production Process: For Game Designers (And Everyone).' That detail positions him not only as a practitioner but also as someone who has written a broader reflection on creative process for both game designers and a wider audience.",
        "title": "Author of A Playful Production Process",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:23.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that Lemarchand's opening emphasizes a mix of personal struggle, academic background, and creative opportunity, which gives the story a memoir-like structure instead of a purely career-focused profile. This suggests the article may use game design as a lens for discussing identity, meaning, and artistic development.",
        "title": "Agent observation on memoir-like framing",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:23.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nLegendary game designer Richard Lemarchand on the importance and joy of playful storytelling.\n\n![](https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/peaceful-village-700x420.jpg)\n\nIn a \"peaceful village\" sequence, Nathan Drake strolls through a Himalayan village on a sunny morning. Screenshot from \"Uncharted 2,\" via [Mocah.org](https://mocah.org/923003-uncharted-4-a-thief039s-end-uncharted-nathan-drake.html)\n\nBy: Richard Lemarchand\n\n[](#)[](#)[](#)[](#)[](#)\n\n*   A↑\n*   A↓\n\n*   Off\n*   Bright\n*   Dark\n*   Blues\n*   Gray\n\n[BeeLine Reader](https://www.beelinereader.com) uses subtle color gradients to help you read more efficiently.\n\nMy game story starts in 1991 in the rural west of England, on the eve of a videogame revolution. I was a 23-year old Oxford graduate with a hard-to-apply Physics & Philosophy degree, a nasty case of undiagnosed situational depression, and an ongoing hunt for meaning in art, including videogames. I couldn’t believe my luck — the rapidly expanding American game publisher MicroProse had a small British studio, where I had won a position as a junior game designer. Despite my lack of professional experience, I discovered that the creative tinkering I’d thought of as play during my childhood and teens counted for a lot, and I threw myself into learning from my brilliant colleagues.\n\n[![](https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/playful-production-1.jpg)](https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/playful-production-process)\n\nRichard Lemarchand is the author of “[A Playful Production Process: For Game Designers (And Everyone)](https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/playful-production-process)“",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 2/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:23.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Four years after his 1991 start in rural west England, Richard Lemarchand says he had pitched up in Palo Alto as a prematurely senior game designer at Crystal Dynamics. He describes the studio as being founded by executives from Sega and Fox TV in the spirit of \"Siliwood,\" meaning a convergence of Silicon Valley technical capability and Hollywood storytelling ambitions.",
        "title": "Move to Crystal Dynamics in Palo Alto",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand says he wanted to make games that told stories that mattered to him in the way his favorite stories did. He explicitly names works such as \"Star Wars,\" \"Do the Right Thing,\" \"Watchmen,\" and \"Sexing the Cherry\" as touchstones for the kind of meaningful storytelling he aspired to bring into games.",
        "title": "Storytelling influences and goals",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He notes that game console storage space had suddenly expanded, which made room for audio and video files and opened radically new possibilities for game storytelling. This detail shows that he viewed technology changes not just as technical upgrades but as creative enablers for narrative experimentation.",
        "title": "Storage expansion enabled new storytelling",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "At Crystal Dynamics, Lemarchand was working on \"Gex,\" a series about a wisecracking gecko trapped in TV land who collected remotes and 1-UPs. He says he loved the wall-sticking gameplay and dad jokes, but still felt compelled to do more with the medium.",
        "title": "Working on Gex and wanting more",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand describes meeting Amy Hennig as an important turning point in his creative development. She introduced him to \"The Writer's Journey,\" Christopher Vogler's screenwriting manual that applies Joseph Campbell's \"hero's journey\" ideas to Hollywood storytelling.",
        "title": "Amy Hennig and The Writer's Journey",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article explains the hero's journey, or monomyth, as a universal story structure based on archetypes and values that Campbell, building on Jung, thought existed beneath mythological systems from around the world. This gives context for why the concept became influential in game and screen storytelling.",
        "title": "Hero's journey and monomyth background",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article includes a warning that, in artless hands, the hero's journey can become formulaic. It says this kind of storytelling often values the acts of individuals over those of collectives or communities, implying a critique of overly simplistic narrative templates.",
        "title": "Critique of formulaic hero's journey",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The source article continues to frame Lemarchand's career as a blend of personal aspiration, technological change, and evolving narrative theory. This chunk adds the specific shift from wanting to tell meaningful stories to encountering Hollywood-influenced story structure through Amy Hennig.",
        "title": "Career shift toward narrative theory",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that Lemarchand's account links game design to a broader media ecology: Hollywood, Silicon Valley, screenwriting manuals, myth theory, and comic-book or literary influences all sit in the same creative field. That suggests his design philosophy was shaped by cross-disciplinary borrowing rather than by game mechanics alone.",
        "title": "Agent observation on cross-disciplinary influences",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) find it significant that he frames increased storage capacity as a narrative turning point. That implies the history of game storytelling is not only about artistic intent, but also about hardware capacity making new forms of expression possible.",
        "title": "Agent observation on hardware and narrative",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) also notice a tension in this passage between aspiration and limitation. Lemarchand loves Gex, yet says he wanted more, which points to a recurring theme in creative careers: enjoying existing work while still sensing a need to push the medium beyond current conventions.",
        "title": "Agent observation on creative dissatisfaction",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nFour years later and I’d pitched up in Palo Alto, now as a prematurely senior game designer at Crystal Dynamics, a studio founded by executives from Sega and Fox TV in the spirit of “Siliwood,” the confluence of Silicon Valley technological chops and Hollywood storytelling. I wanted to make games that told stories, stories that meant something in the way that my favorite stories did — from “Star Wars” to “Do the Right Thing_,_“ “Watchmen” to “Sexing the Cherry_._” Game console storage space had just exploded in size, and now we had room for the audio and video files that were making radically new things possible in game storytelling. I was working on “Gex_,”_ a series about a wisecracking gecko trapped in TV land, collecting remotes and 1-UPs. I loved “Gex” for the wall-sticking gameplay and dad jokes, but I wanted to do _more_. Then I met Amy Hennig, the game director, who introduced me to “The Writer’s Journey,” Christopher Vogler’s famous screenwriting manual that brought Joseph Campbell’s anthropological ideas about the “hero’s journey” to Hollywood. The hero’s journey, or _monomyth_, is the universal story, archetypes, and values that Campbell (building on Jung) saw beneath mythological systems from around the world.\n\n> In artless hands, the hero’s journey often results in formulaic stories that value the acts of individuals over those of collectives or communities.",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 3/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:16:43.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand argues that videogames have long struggled with story, and that game developers and scholars have sharply disagreed about whether narrative matters in games at all. He contrasts those who see story as irrelevant or distracting with those who see games as promising spaces for richly interactive and immersive storytelling, framing this as a core tension in game studies and game design.",
        "title": "Games, story, and a long-running debate",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:02.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He says that, for him, everything in every art form can be understood as narrative because the mind itself is a narrativizing mechanism. This is presented as a personal philosophy that has guided his entire career, especially his attempt to solve the problem of putting games and story together in a way that truly works.",
        "title": "Mind as a narrativizing mechanism",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:02.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand describes the common structure of many videogames as placing the player inside a player-character and sending them into a fantastical world of mystery and surprise. In his account, the pair cross thresholds, learn new skills from mentors, defeat enemies, complete tasks, and move toward ultimate victory and savior status, which he says maps very neatly onto the hero’s journey.",
        "title": "Videogames mapped to the hero's journey",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:02.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He suggests that the alignment between videogame structures and the hero’s journey helps explain why game developers are often drawn to the monomyth when first learning storytelling. The implication is that the pattern feels intuitively useful because many games already echo the same progression of departure, training, challenge, and triumph.",
        "title": "Why developers gravitate to the monomyth",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:03.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "This passage extends the earlier theme that Lemarchand’s design thinking is shaped by narrative theory as much as by mechanics. Here, he explicitly treats the hero’s journey not just as an external theory he encountered, but as a structure that games naturally resemble and therefore continually tempt developers to use.",
        "title": "Agent reflection on games and monomyth",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:03.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that this chunk strengthens the article’s central thesis: games are not just entertainment systems with occasional story, but narrative machines that already encode story-like progressions. That makes Lemarchand’s career argument feel less like adding narrative onto games and more like learning how to recognize the stories games are already telling through structure and progression.",
        "title": "Agent reflection on narrative already inside games",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:03.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nVideogames have often struggled with story. Both game developers and scholars of game studies have argued vehemently about the role of narrative in games, some claiming that it’s irrelevant or a distraction, while others see the promise of richly interactive and immersive storytelling spaces. For me, everything in every art form can be seen as narrative, because the mind is a narrativizing mechanism, and my whole career has been built on tackling the challenge that game developers and game writers face when they try to put games and story together in a way that really works. In many videogames, the player is embodied in a player-character, and is transported to a fantastical world of mystery and surprise. Together they cross thresholds, get trained up in new skills by mentors, defeat enemies, and complete tasks, progressing towards ultimate victory and savior status. This all maps very neatly onto the hero’s journey, and so perhaps it’s natural that we game developers gravitate towards the monomyth as we begin to learn about storytelling.",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 4/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:03.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand says the hero’s journey can be deeply problematic because it centers brave boys traveling to far-off lands to seize treasures and bring prosperity home. He explicitly connects this to colonialist and patriarchal assumptions, arguing that the model is not neutral and can encode harmful values even while it remains influential in storytelling and game design.",
        "title": "Critique of colonial and patriarchal hero narratives",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He extends the critique of the monomyth by linking it to some 4X strategy games, which he describes through the genre’s notorious four Xs: explore, expand, exploit, and exterminate. This comparison suggests that certain game genres can reproduce the same imperial logic found in conquest-driven hero narratives, making the storytelling critique also a critique of game design assumptions.",
        "title": "Hero's journey and 4X genre critique",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand warns that when handled without care, the hero’s journey produces formulaic stories that overvalue individual acts and undervalue collectives or communities. He presents this as a structural weakness of the model, not just a matter of taste, and implies that richer storytelling should account for group agency rather than only singular heroic triumphs.",
        "title": "Formulaic individualism in story structure",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Campbell and Vogler’s writing pushed Lemarchand into a personal quest to learn more about what is now called story structure. He says he began searching for patterns that would help game designers make storytelling games in which gameplay and story work together smoothly rather than pulling apart at the seams.",
        "title": "Quest to understand story structure",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He describes himself as having a highly analytical brain, and says that stories had previously mostly washed over him, creating emotion and fascination without conscious analysis. Through this work, he began to understand what was happening under the hood of the stories he loved and to think that reverse-engineering them might reveal which storytelling techniques could actually work in videogames.",
        "title": "Reverse-engineering stories for games",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand frames his growing interest in story structure as a shift from passive appreciation to active analysis. The passage suggests he was moving toward a design philosophy where understanding narrative mechanics became a practical tool for building better videogame storytelling, not merely an academic exercise.",
        "title": "From story absorption to narrative analysis",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that this chunk clarifies a major ethical turn in the article: Lemarchand does not just celebrate the hero’s journey as a useful template, but interrogates its embedded politics and its tendency toward individualism. That makes his relationship to storytelling feel more critical and reflexive than simple enthusiasm for Campbell or Vogler.",
        "title": "Agent reflection on ethical critique of monomyth",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) find it significant that he uses the phrase 'under the hood' for stories, because it presents narrative as something engineered and inspectable rather than mystical. That language fits the article’s larger theme that game designers can learn by studying the hidden systems behind stories, much as they study systems in games.",
        "title": "Agent reflection on narrative as a system",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nOf course, there’s a big problem with a storytelling model that revolves around brave boys traveling to far-off lands to seize treasures and bring prosperity home: It’s easy to identify the hero’s journey as colonialist and patriarchal. (The same goes for certain game genres, such as the “4X” strategy game style, with its grisly four Xs of “explore, expand, exploit, and exterminate.”) Another issue is that, in artless hands, the hero’s journey often results in formulaic stories that value the acts of individuals over those of collectives or communities. But Campbell and Vogler got me thinking, and set me on my own quest to learn more about what we now call _story structure_, looking out for patterns that would help game designers make storytelling games where the gameplay and story work nicely together, instead of pulling apart at the seams. I have a pretty analytical brain, and while stories had always just washed over me, weaving their magic spells of emotion and interest, I was starting to understand what was going on under the hood of the stories I loved, and to realize that maybe by reverse-engineering them, we could find out what storytelling techniques _would_ work in a videogame.",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 5/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:15.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Richard Lemarchand says he worked with Amy Hennig for about 13 years. Their collaboration began on the cult classic \"Gnostic horror\" game series \"Soul Reaver\" at Crystal Dynamics and later continued at Naughty Dog, where their team created the world of \"Uncharted.\" He notes that the recent \"Uncharted\" movie starring Tom Holland as treasure hunter Nathan Drake is part of the broader cultural afterlife of that work.",
        "title": "Lemarchand and Hennig collaboration history",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "At Naughty Dog, Lemarchand and Hennig continued studying story structure using screenwriting books such as Blake Snyder's \"Save the Cat\" and Robert McKee's \"Story.\" He says both books influenced \"Uncharted\" by helping the team learn how to introduce likable, interesting characters, orient them toward goals, place obstacles in their path, and show them growing through struggle.",
        "title": "Story structure books that shaped Uncharted",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand highlights Robert McKee's idea of \"the gap,\" which he defines as the difference between what a protagonist expects will happen when they take an action to achieve a goal and the actual result that follows. This concept appears to have been especially useful for thinking about dramatic tension and unexpected consequences in narrative design.",
        "title": "McKee's concept of the gap",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He says \"Story\" and \"Save the Cat\" are not perfect books, but they are useful for storytellers who are learning the ropes. He especially values them for nonlinear fields like game design, where creators need to take story apart and then reassemble it in an interactive context.",
        "title": "Practical value of screenwriting manuals for games",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The passage reinforces Lemarchand's view that game design sits in a nonlinear storytelling space, meaning designers cannot simply import film or novel structure unchanged. Instead, they have to deconstruct story mechanics and rebuild them in forms that can work with player agency and interactivity.",
        "title": "Story structure must be rebuilt for interactivity",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that this chunk shows how Lemarchand's narrative training became increasingly concrete and tool-based. He is no longer just admiring story theory in the abstract; he is using specific craft frameworks to shape character presentation, goal-setting, obstacle design, and transformation arcs in games.",
        "title": "Agent observation on practical narrative toolkit",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) find it significant that Lemarchand frames \"Save the Cat\" and \"Story\" as imperfect rather than authoritative. That suggests a mature design attitude: use theory as a scaffold, but stay willing to adapt or question it when the interactive medium demands something different.",
        "title": "Agent observation on theory as scaffold",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nAmy Hennig and I worked together for about 13 years, first on the cult classic “Gnostic horror” game series “Soul Reaver” at Crystal Dynamics, and then at Naughty Dog, a studio in Sony’s videogames division, where our team created the world of “Uncharted” (you might have seen the recent “Uncharted” movie featuring Tom Holland as treasure hunter Nathan Drake). We continued our studies in story structure at Naughty Dog, using other screenwriting books like Blake Snyder’s “Save the Cat” and Robert McKee’s “Story.” Both these books had an influence on “Uncharted,” as we learned how to introduce likable, interesting characters, orient them to their goals and the obstacles in their path, and then show them growing as people through the ensuing struggle. For example, McKee talks about “the gap,” the differential between what a protagonist expects will happen when they take an action to achieve a goal, and the actual outcome that results. “Story” and “Save the Cat” aren’t perfect, but they’re useful to storytellers who are learning the ropes, and very useful for storytellers in nonlinear fields — like game design — who are trying to pick apart story and put it back together for an interactive context.",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 6/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:34.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Richard Lemarchand describes teaching game designers story structure through three-act Aristotelian dramatics and Freytag’s famous pyramid. He says these frameworks provide a tidy beginning-middle-end pattern of setup, development, and resolution, which helps developers recognize similar rising and falling intensity in both stories and games. He connects this to players struggling against each other or against the game system to reach goals and win.",
        "title": "Story structure frameworks for game designers",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand says peaks of intensity in gameplay and story can either reinforce each other or cancel each other out. His framing suggests that effective game narrative design depends on balancing emotional and mechanical crescendos so they support rather than compete with each other. This makes pacing a central craft problem in interactive storytelling.",
        "title": "Gameplay and story intensity can align or clash",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "In Uncharted, Lemarchand and his team intentionally alternated intense popcorn-movie action with quieter spaces of exploration and reflection. He presents this as a radical design choice for big-budget games at the time, because it allowed the emotional story space to breathe instead of being overwhelmed by constant action.",
        "title": "Uncharted pacing of action and reflection",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand says he helped create the peaceful village sequence in Uncharted 2: Among Thieves. In that section, the combat systems are turned off and Nathan Drake strolls through a Himalayan village on a sunny morning, visiting kindly people with whom he shares no common language. He says the sequence was considered risky in 2009 but was met with wildly positive responses from critics and fans.",
        "title": "Uncharted 2 peaceful village sequence",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The peaceful village sequence in Uncharted 2 is used as an example of noncombat storytelling through atmosphere, exploration, and social observation rather than mechanical challenge. The scene’s value lies in making room for contemplation and human connection inside a blockbuster action game. It shows that removing combat can itself become a meaningful design gesture.",
        "title": "Noncombat storytelling in Uncharted 2",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand frames the peaceful village sequence as evidence that quiet interludes can deepen a game’s emotional impact. By slowing the pace and giving players a chance to simply move through a place, the game lets the story and setting register more fully. The positive critical and fan response suggests that audiences were receptive to this kind of formal experimentation.",
        "title": "Quiet interludes deepen game emotion",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article links Lemarchand’s book A Playful Production Process with his broader interest in story structure for game designers. He uses the book to explain how dramatic forms such as three-act structure and Freytag’s pyramid can be adapted into a game-design context. This positions him as someone translating literary and theatrical theory into practical tools for interactive media.",
        "title": "Lemarchand on adapting dramatic form for games",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice this chunk sharpens one of the article’s key claims: game storytelling is not just about adding plot to gameplay, but about engineering rhythm between tension and release. The peaceful village sequence is significant because it demonstrates that restraint, pause, and exploration can be as narratively important as action. That makes pacing itself a storytelling mechanic.",
        "title": "Agent observation on pacing as narrative mechanic",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) find it significant that Lemarchand describes the village sequence as risky at the time. That detail suggests innovation in games often requires challenging assumptions about what blockbuster audiences will tolerate. The later positive reception also implies that audience expectations may expand when designers trust quieter forms of play.",
        "title": "Agent observation on risk and audience response",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nIn my book “[A Playful Production Process: For Game Designers (and Everyone)](https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/playful-production-process),” I talk about “story structure for game designers,” laying out some ideas about three-act Aristotelian dramatics and [Freytag’s famous pyramid](https://writers.com/freytags-pyramid), both of which have a tidy “beginning-middle-end” structure of set-up, development, and resolution. This helps game developers see the same rising and falling patterns of intensity in stories that they see in the games they make, as players vie against each other, or against the system of the game, to achieve their goals and win. Peaks of intensity in gameplay and story can sometimes work with each other to create wonderful moments in a synergetic way, but at other times they might cancel each other out.\n\nFor example, in the “Uncharted” games we made sure to alternate sequences of intense popcorn-movie action gameplay with quieter spaces of exploration and reflection — something radical for the time, in big-budget games — to give the emotion in the story space to breathe. I was part of a group that created the “peaceful village” sequence in “Uncharted 2: Among Thieves,” where the combat systems of the game are turned off, and Drake strolls through a Himalayan village on a sunny morning, visiting with kindly people with whom he shares no common language. This was deemed a risky game design choice in 2009, and we were delighted by the wildly positive responses it prompted from critics and fans alike.\n\n> In the “Uncharted” games we made sure to alternate sequences of intense popcorn-movie action gameplay with quieter spaces of exploration and reflection.",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 7/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:17:55.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Richard Lemarchand introduces Frank Daniel’s idea of sequence structure, describing acts as standalone tales that can be divided into sequences, and sequences further into scenes and individual beats. He says Daniel was a Czech-American screenwriter, film director, and sometimes dean of the USC School of Cinematic Arts. This adds a more granular storytelling framework to the article’s earlier discussion of three-act structure and Freytag’s pyramid.",
        "title": "Frank Daniel sequence structure",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand says Melanie Anne Phillips and Chris Huntley of Dramatica fame taught him that stories are fractal. In his account, acts are made up of sequences, sequences are made up of scenes, and scenes are made up of beats such as a joke, a glare, or a tender moment. He presents this as a nested, self-similar model of storytelling that can scale from large arcs down to tiny expressive details.",
        "title": "Stories as fractal structures",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article says this fractal view transformed Lemarchand’s thinking about both storytelling and games. He now sees them as modular, interlocking, overlapping patterns of beginning-middle-end repeated with variation to produce endlessly fascinating situations. This frames game design as an exercise in assembling smaller narrative units into larger emotional effects.",
        "title": "Modular pattern view of games and story",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand argues that if designers can identify each beginning-middle-end inside a gameplay sequence or story fragment, they can deliberately collage those fragments together to create stronger audience effects. He says this applies to both thrilling and moving outcomes for players. The wording suggests that pacing, sequencing, and juxtaposition are conscious compositional tools rather than accidental byproducts.",
        "title": "Deliberate collage of story fragments",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He gives a cinematic example of a lightsaber battle climax in which Darth Vader reveals a key piece of family information to his adversary. Lemarchand says this turns a swordfight into an unforgettable moment of cinematic history because the emotional revelation changes the meaning of the action. He uses this to illustrate how story beats can recontextualize gameplay or spectacle at the peak of intensity.",
        "title": "Lightsaber battle revelation example",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand compares that film example to betrayals in Uncharted 2, saying they play a similar role in twisting the story toward unexpected and exciting new directions. The comparison suggests that sudden narrative reversals can reshape the emotional trajectory of a game just as a dramatic revelation can in cinema. It also reinforces his interest in how action and story can intersect at the same moment without competing with each other.",
        "title": "Uncharted 2 betrayal as narrative twist",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:17.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The passage reveals that Lemarchand’s design thinking is now strongly organized around nested form: acts, sequences, scenes, and beats all become reusable units for both story and gameplay. He treats these units as building blocks that can be recombined with variation to generate surprise and emotional resonance. This suggests a highly compositional approach to interactive storytelling.",
        "title": "Nested units in interactive storytelling",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:17.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice this chunk pushes the article further into systems thinking by treating narrative as a scalable architecture. The key move is not simply borrowing film structure, but understanding how small emotional beats can be embedded inside larger gameplay patterns. That makes the medium feel less like a linear script and more like a designed ecosystem of tension, revelation, and release.",
        "title": "Agent observation on narrative architecture",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:17.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) find the Darth Vader example significant because it shows Lemarchand using a famous pop-culture scene to explain formal principles of storytelling. The point is not the specific franchise but the structural effect: action becomes memorable when it is interrupted or transformed by information that changes the stakes. That is a useful bridge between cinematic theory and game narrative design.",
        "title": "Agent observation on revelation and stakes",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:17.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that the mention of Uncharted 2 betrayals suggests Lemarchand values twists that emerge from within the action rather than from detached exposition. This implies a preference for integrated storytelling, where plot developments are embedded in the flow of play. That is consistent with the article’s broader emphasis on gameplay and narrative as mutually shaping forces.",
        "title": "Agent observation on integrated twists",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:17.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nThere is also “sequence structure,” a storytelling model proposed by Frank Daniel, the Czech-American screenwriter, film director, and sometime dean of the USC School of Cinematic Arts. For Daniel, the three or five acts of a story can each be regarded as a standalone tale, and each act can be broken down further into sequences, which can _also_ be seen as miniature stories, one leading into the next. This led me to an idea from Melanie Anne Phillips and Chris Huntley of “Dramatica” fame, who tell us that stories are fractal — as acts are made up of sequences, sequences are made up of scenes, and further down into individual “beats,” where a joke is told, a fierce glare is shot across a room, or a tender moment is shared.\n\nThis transformed my thinking about both storytelling and games, which I now see as modular, interlocking, overlapping patterns of beginning-middle-end, repeated with variation to create endlessly fascinating situations. If we can identify each beginning-middle-end in a sequence of gameplay or a fragment of story, we can be deliberate about the way we collage them together to create thrilling and moving effects for our audience of players. One good example of this is the way that, at the height of an intense and action-packed lightsaber battle, one D. Vader drops a key piece of family information for his adversary, turning the climax of a swordfight into an unforgettable moment of cinematic history. If you’re a fan of “Uncharted 2,” you might remember the betrayals in that game, which play a similar role in twisting the story towards unexpected and exciting new directions.",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 8/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:17.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Richard Lemarchand says game players are very goal-oriented, just like story characters, and that good game design depends on holding the tension between what the player-character wants in the game world and what the real player wants at any given moment. He argues that superior game stories are ones where the cares and goals of the player-character are aligned with the player’s own cares and goals, so that narrative, gameplay, and player psychology reinforce one another rather than pull apart.",
        "title": "Alignment of player and player-character goals",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:36.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand expands his storytelling framework beyond narrative and mechanics by saying that game design, narrative design, player psychology, and even the cultural, social, or political context of a game are braided together. This suggests he does not treat story as an isolated layer on top of gameplay, but as part of a wider system of meaning that includes context and audience experience.",
        "title": "Braided layers of game meaning",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:36.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "He says his deep dives into art, culture, and design may have helped his situational depression improve over time. He describes taking solace in art throughout his life, finding meaning in art museums and in the progressive emotional accomplishments of indie game designers, but even more so in the act of artmaking itself through game design and development.",
        "title": "Art and game making as personal solace",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:36.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "Lemarchand presents collaboration with extraordinarily talented people as a major source of meaning in his career. He says that working together to push out the bounds of what was possible in storytelling games gave him purpose, and he hopes that introducing a healthier game development process to the next generation can help sow seeds of change.",
        "title": "Collaborative craft and healthier development",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:36.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article’s author biography identifies Richard Lemarchand as a game designer with more than 20 years in the videogame industry and as an Associate Professor in the USC Games program at the University of Southern California. It also states that he led or co-led the design of all three PlayStation 3 Uncharted games, including the award-winning Uncharted 2: Among Thieves, and that he wrote A Playful Production Process: For Game Designers (And Everyone).",
        "title": "Richard Lemarchand biography and credentials",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:36.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The article is dated May 5, 2022, and was published by The MIT Press Reader under the title My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling. It is tagged with Game Design and Video Games, which situates the piece as both a reflective career essay and a design-oriented media article.",
        "title": "Article publication details",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:37.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that this closing passage broadens the article from craft theory into an explicitly humanistic argument about well-being, meaning, and work culture. Lemarchand is not only interested in making better games; he is also linking creative practice to mental health, personal resilience, and the possibility of healthier industry norms.",
        "title": "Agent observation on creative practice and well-being",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:37.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) find it significant that Lemarchand describes the alignment between player goals and player-character goals as the 'good design track.' That phrasing suggests he treats alignment not as a bonus but as a core principle of successful interactive storytelling, where narrative coherence and player motivation need to be designed together.",
        "title": "Agent observation on goal alignment as design principle",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:37.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "# My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling\n\nGame players are very goal-oriented, just like the characters in stories, and if we can hold the tension between what the player-character (the hero or avatar in the game) wants inside the story world of the game, and what the _player_ is going for at any given moment, then we’re on a good design track. It’s my belief that superior game stories are those where the cares and goals of the player-character are aligned with the player’s own cares and goals, a place where game design, narrative design, player psychology, and even the cultural, social, or political context of the game are braided together.\n\nMaybe thanks to my deep dives into art, culture, and design, my situational depression improved over time. I’ve always taken solace in art, and I found a lot of the meaning I was looking for, everywhere from art museums to the progressive, emotional accomplishments of indie game designers. But moreso, I found meaning in artmaking, in the craft of game design and development, collaborating with extraordinarily talented people to push out the bounds of what was possible in storytelling games. Hopefully, introducing a healthier game development process to the next generation can help sow a few more seeds of change.\n\n* * *\n\n_**Richard Lemarchand**, a game designer who worked in the videogame industry for more than 20 years, is Associate Professor in the USC Games program at the University of Southern California. Among many other projects, he led or co-led the design of all three games in the PlayStation 3 Uncharted series, including the award-winning “Uncharted 2: Among Thieves.” He is the author of “[A Playful Production Process: For Game Designers (And Everyone)](https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/playful-production-process).”_\n\nPosted on May 5, 2022\n\n[Facebook](#) [Twitter](#) [Bluesky](#) [Reddit](#) [Flipboard](#)\n\nTagged in\n\n[Game Design](/tag/game-design/) [Video Games](/tag/video-games/)",
        "title": "My Game Story: Reflections on Design and Storytelling - Part 9/12",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-23T21:18:37.000Z",
        "source": "https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/my-game-story-reflections-on-design-and-storytelling/"
      },
      {
        "content": "The chunk contains a MIT Press donation prompt explaining that The MIT Press is a mission-driven, not-for-profit scholarly publisher. It says reader support helps enable open publishing models and the production of books with superior design quality, which frames the publication as value-driven rather than purely commercial.",
